                                                                                                               Sasan cash in place
          OUR BUREAU                          Power punch                                  
	Mumbai, April 21: Sasan Power Ltd  a subsidiary of Anil Ambani-controlled Reliance Power Ltd  has tied up debt amounting to Rs 14,550 crore for the Sasan mega power project. It hopes to commission the first phase of the project by March 2012.         
	A consortium of 14 banks and financial institutions, with the State Bank of India as the lead lender, have put in place the entire debt component of the project located in Singrauli district, Madhya Pradesh, said a press release issued by Reliance Power.         
	This makes Sasan the largest project that has been financed with debt across industries in the country, the release added.        
	It is also the first mega power project to attain financial closure.         
	The estimated project cost of Rs 19,400 crore is funded on a 75:25 debt-equity ratio basis. Other banks and institutions that have signed financing agreements with Sasan Power include IIFCL (India amp; UK), Power Finance Corporation, Rural Electrification Corporation, Punjab National Bank, Life Insurance Corporation, Axis Bank and IDBI Bank.         
	According to a Reliance Power spokesperson, the commissioning date of the first phase of the project, comprising two units with a total capacity of 1,320MW, has been advanced from 2013-end to March 2012.         
	An engineering, procurement and construction contract has been awarded to Reliance Infrastructure while orders for equipment to be used in the main plant have been placed with Chinas Shanghai Electric.         
	Several international consultants such as Black amp; Veatch, Toshiba, SNC and HOK (Singapore) are working on the project.                                                                                                                                                      
